Pre-heat your #oven{} to 180 degrees. Cut the @courgette{2} in half lengthways and
scrape out the soft seedy middle with a #spoon{}. Put the courgette 'boats' on
a #baking tray{} with a drizzle of @olive oil{drizzle} and pop in your oven
to cook for ~{15%minutes}, then remove and keep to the side. Turn your oven up
to 200 degrees.

Meanwhile, peel and finely chop the @echalion shallot{1}(peeled and finely chopped)
and @garlic clove{1}(peeled and finely chopped) and chop the @button mushrooms{1}(chopped
into roughly 1cm pieces). Chop the @cherry tomatoes{1} in half.

Add a splash of @olive oil{splash} to a #frying pan{} on medium heat and add your
echalion shallot, cook for ~{3%minutes} before adding your garlic and cooking
for a further ~{1%minute}. Add your mushrooms to the pan with a pinch of @salt{pinch}
and a good grind of @black pepper{grind} and cook for ~{5-7%minutes}, or until
all the liquid has been absorbed back into the mushrooms.

Take the pan off the heat, add the @crème fraîche{1} to the pan and stir through.
Spoon your mushroom mixture equally into each courgette boat.

Mix the @panko breadcrumbs{pinch} and @grated hard Italian style cheese{2} together
and sprinkle the mixture on top of your stuffed courgettes. Grind over some
@black pepper{grind} and put in your oven to cook for ~{15-20%minutes} or until
the crusts are lovely and brown.

In the meantime, add your tomatoes to a separate baking tray, drizzle over half
the @balsamic vinegar{1/2} and a splash of @olive oil{splash}, a pinch of @salt{pinch}
and a good grind of @black pepper{grind} and put in your oven to cook for
~{8-10%minutes}.

While your courgettes and tomatoes are cooking, mix the rest of the @balsamic vinegar{1/2}
with another splash of @olive oil{splash}. Add this to the @baby spinach{1} and
toss it together.

When your courgettes and tomatoes are cooked, get them out of your oven. Add
your tomatoes along with any excess oil and balsamic vinegar from the baking tray
to your spinach, along with the @munchy seeds{pinch}(sesame sprinkle) and toss
together again. Serve your courgettes with your salad on the side and enjoy!

> Stuffing one food into another food is somewhat of an obsession for us humans. Wherever you find yourself in the world, there's always SOMETHING stuffed on the menu. But we wonder where this obsession came from? We like to think that there was a boy called Bob and his mum said, "No Bob, you can't have any mushrooms–it's courgette night" and Bob defiantly hid the mushrooms inside the courgette.